This is a classic gotcha when moving from ASP.NET Core to MAUI.

**In ASP.NET Core**, a new DI scope is created per HTTP request, so `AddScoped<MyDbContext>()` gives you a fresh instance per request.

**In MAUI, there is no per-request scope.** The app runs in a single long-lived scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your `DbContext` is created once and reused forever — stale data, tracked entities piling up, etc.

### Fixes

**Option 1 — Use `AddTransient`:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();
```
Each page/service injection gets a new instance. Simple, but you lose shared-context-per-unit-of-work.

**Option 2 — Use `IServiceScopeFactory` to create manual scopes:**
```csharp
public class MyViewModel
{
    private readonly IServiceScopeFactory _scopeFactory;

    public MyViewModel(IServiceScopeFactory scopeFactory)
        => _scopeFactory = scopeFactory;

    public async Task LoadDataAsync()
    {
        using var scope = _scopeFactory.CreateScope();
        var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();
        // db is fresh and disposed when scope ends
    }
}
```
This mirrors the per-request pattern from ASP.NET Core and gives you explicit lifetime control.

**Option 2 is generally preferred** — it keeps the DbContext short-lived and properly disposed, which avoids the change-tracking bloat and stale-data issues you're seeing.
